## Internationalization (i18n)

### Four languages from day one
- **da** — Dansk (primary)
- **en** — English
- **de** — Deutsch
- **sv** — Svenska

Same rules as web:
- NEVER hardcode strings in JSX.
- Every new UI string goes into ALL FOUR locale files simultaneously.
- Reuse `common.*` keys where they exist on web.
- Use nested dot-notation keys (`indeklima.sensors.empty_state`, not
  `emptySensorsState`).

### Usage
```tsx
import { useTranslation } from 'react-i18next';

const { t } = useTranslation();
return <Text>{t('common.loading')}</Text>;
```

---

## Authentication

### Firebase JWT everywhere
- Login via `signInWithEmailAndPassword` (Firebase Web SDK). Google via
  `expo-auth-session`. No native Firebase SDK — keeps Expo Go compatibility.
- Token is fetched via `getIdToken()` and attached to every API request as
  `Authorization: Bearer <token>`.
- On 401, the API client forces a token refresh and retries once (same
  pattern as `apiClient.js` on web).
- Tenant is sent via `X-Tenant-Id` header — the backend validates against
  `user_tenants` before trusting it. Never trusted blindly.

### Sensitive data
- Firebase auto-persists the refresh token in SecureStore (keychain on iOS,
  EncryptedSharedPreferences on Android) via the React Native Firebase
  persistence adapter we configure in `src/services/auth/firebase.ts`.
- MMKV is NOT used for tokens. It is unencrypted by default.
- On logout, clear the full query cache + all `roomalyzer_*` storage keys
  + sign out of Firebase. Fire-and-forget each step.

### MFA / 2FA
- Tenants can require 2FA (`tenant_requires_2fa`). If the backend returns
  the enrollment-required flag, block app access until TOTP is set up.
- Re-use the web's MFA flow conceptually: show QR / secret, verify 6-digit
  code, enroll.

---

## API & Data Layer

### Hono API — the single source of truth
The mobile app NEVER talks directly to Legacy. It always goes through the
Hono API at `env.apiBaseUrl` (default `https://v2.roomalyzer.com`). The
same "Strict Data Boundary" rule from the web repo applies:

- If an endpoint is broken on the server, STOP and report to the user.
  Never shim missing data client-side. Never persist Legacy-owned data in
  local storage as a "bridge". This is a hard rule — violating it creates
  shadow state and hides real bugs.

### Generated OpenAPI client
```
npm run gen:api        # fetches prod spec and regenerates src/services/api/schema.ts
npm run gen:api:local  # uses http://localhost:3001 (pair with web repo dev server)
```

- ALWAYS go through the typed client (`src/services/api/client.ts`).
- No ad-hoc `fetch()` calls in components or features.
- Commit the generated `schema.ts` so API changes appear as diffs.
- When adjusting the server's Zod schemas, regenerate and review the diff
  before pushing.

### TanStack Query
- Every read goes through a `useQuery` hook in `src/features/*/hooks.ts`.
- Every write goes through a `useMutation` — with `onSuccess` that invalidates
  the relevant query keys.
- Query keys follow a hierarchical pattern: `['indeklima', 'sensors', { tenantId }]`
  so tenant-switching can bulk-invalidate with one call.

### Offline / cache strategy — tiered
The "read all historical data offline" goal is satisfied by this tiered
cache (stored via `persistQueryClient` + MMKV/AsyncStorage):

| Tier | Scope | Lifetime |
|------|-------|----------|
| **Snapshot** | Latest reading of every sensor the user has access to | 24 h `staleTime`, GC on tenant switch |
| **Raw** | 5-min resolution history, last 7 days, for sensors the user has opened | 7 days, LRU-evicted at 50 MB cap |
| **Downsampled** | Hour/day resolution, last 30 days / 1 year | 30 days |
| **On-demand** | Older than 1 year | Not cached, fetched online only |

Invalidation on tenant switch: `queryClient.clear()` + re-hydrate from persister.

### Location restrictions
Users can be restricted to specific locations (`allowed_locations`). A
`useLocationFilter` hook (in `src/hooks/`) filters sensors, trees, and
flat lists by `location` field. Apply it on EVERY page that displays
location-grouped data — exactly like the web app.

