## UI Design System

### Color tokens — MUST use Tailwind classes or `colors` from `src/theme`
See `tailwind.config.js` and `src/theme/colors.ts`. Brand: `#5D7C8F`,
`#3498DB`, `#2C3E50`. Status: `#6c9e83`, `#f0ad4e`, `#d65b5b`. Background:
`#F4F6F9`.

### Dusty palette — MANDATORY
Whenever any UI element needs a color (chart series, badge, scenario tag,
module accent), pick from the dusty palette in `src/theme/colors.ts`:
```
#5D7C8F  dusty blue-gray       (brand)
#6c9e83  dusty sage green      (status-good)
#f0ad4e  dusty amber / gold    (status-warn)
#d65b5b  dusty red             (status-bad — alarms only)
#2C3E50  dark navy blue        (brand-dark)
#7a8c7e  muted sage
#8e7c5d  warm taupe
#5b8fa1  steel teal
```
NEVER use saturated colors like `#e67e22`, `#2ecc71`, `#e74c3c` unless the
user explicitly requests it. `#d65b5b` is reserved for serious states —
never decorative.

### Typography
Inter 300/400/500/600/700 loaded via `@expo-google-fonts/inter` in
`app/_layout.tsx`. Use the `type.*` styles from `src/theme/typography.ts`
(`pageTitle`, `sectionLabel`, `body`, `caption`, `kpiValue`, ...) — never
inline fontSize/fontFamily.

### Icons
Use the `<Icon name="..." />` wrapper in `src/components/Icon.tsx`. Pass
names as Bootstrap Icons would (e.g. `thermometer-half`, `droplet`,
`bell`). The wrapper maps to the closest MaterialCommunityIcons glyph.

NEVER import from `@expo/vector-icons` directly in features — always go
through `<Icon>` so we keep one mapping table.

### Primitives (required building blocks)
All screens MUST be built on these primitives — never hand-roll the
equivalent markup:

- `<PageHeading icon="..." title="..." subtitle="..." />` — top of every screen
- `<SectionCard title="..." icon="...">` — rounded card with optional header
- `<SectionLabel>` — tiny uppercase group label
- `<FormField label="..." error="...">` + `<FormInput>` / `<FormSelect>`
  / `<FormSearch>` / `<FormPassword>` / `<FormToggle>`
- `<SegmentedControl options={...} value={...} onChange={...} />` — pick one of 2-5
- `<SensorPicker>` — single sensor select (flat list with hierarchy)
- `<LoadingIndicator>` — full-screen or inline loading
- `<ErrorBanner>` — dismissible page-level error / warning
- `<ConfirmModal>` — bottom-sheet for destructive / dangerous confirmations
- `<Button variant="primary|ghost|danger">` — all CTA
- `<HeroBackButton label="..." onPress={...} />` — dusty-brand pill
  back button for dark hero headers on inner detail pages
- `<KpiTile label="..." value="..." unit="..." icon="..." active={...}
  onPress={...} />` — white rounded metric tile for 2×2 (or 1–4) grids.
  Parent must be a `flexDirection: 'row'` row; tile takes `flex: 1`.

If a needed variant is missing, extend the primitive — do NOT fork inside
a feature.

### Pressable rendering quirk — IMPORTANT
In this Expo SDK 54 + NativeWind v4 setup, **function-style `style`**
on `<Pressable>` has been observed to sporadically drop
`backgroundColor`, `borderWidth/borderColor`, and shadow properties at
render time, leaving the inner content visible on a transparent square.

When building new pressable primitives:
- Apply only layout-neutral styles to the `<Pressable>` itself (e.g.
  `flex: 1`, `alignSelf`, `opacity` for pressed feedback, `transform`).
- Put the actual visual styling — background, borders, shadows,
  padding — on an inner `<View>`.
- Prefer `haptic.*()` inside the `onPress` callback over relying on the
  pressed-state style function for feedback.

`HeroBackButton` and `KpiTile` are the reference implementations.

### Mobile-specific rules
- Respect the safe area on every screen (`SafeAreaView` or
  `useSafeAreaInsets`).
- Use `KeyboardAvoidingView` around forms.
- Every list supports pull-to-refresh via `RefreshControl` → TanStack
  Query's `refetch()`.
- Destructive actions use `Haptics.notificationAsync(Error)` before firing.
- Minimum touch target: 44×44 px (iOS HIG / WCAG). Use `TOUCH_TARGET`
  from `src/theme/spacing.ts`.
- Prefer bottom sheets over centered modals for single-purpose flows.

---

## State Management

- **Server state** → TanStack Query. Nothing else.
- **User prefs / aktivt tenant / aktivt modul** → Zustand store in
  `src/stores/`, persisted via `zustand/middleware/persist` with the
  storage wrapper.
- **Ephemeral UI state** → `useState` / `useReducer` in components.
- **NEVER** reach into `storage` directly from a component — go through
  a store or a hook.

---

## Multi-Tenant Rules

- Active tenant lives in `tenantStore` (Zustand), persisted under
  `roomalyzer_active_tenant`.
- Every API call attaches `X-Tenant-Id`. The backend authoritatively
  validates membership — the mobile app never trusts itself on this.
- Tenant switch flow: set new tenant → `queryClient.clear()` →
  re-hydrate from persister. Do NOT keep previous tenant's cached data
  reachable.

---

## Architecture & Security — Trusted Subsystem Boundary

The mobile app is a thin client. All identity decisions happen in Hono;
Legacy is treated as a trusted subsystem that only Hono may speak to.

```
[Mobile app]  ──HTTPS──>  [Hono v2 API]  ──HTTPS, private VPC──>  [Legacy PHP]
   Firebase ID-token         INTERNAL_API_SECRET (Bearer)
   X-Tenant-Id               X-Tenant-ID / X-User-ID (from verified JWT)
   X-Request-Id              X-Request-Id (forwarded)
```

Reference implementations:
- Mobile client: `src/services/api/client.ts` (only ever hits
  `${env.apiBaseUrl}/api/...`).
- Hono → Legacy: `../roomalyzer20/server/legacyClient.js`.
- JWT verification + tenant resolution:
  `../roomalyzer20/server/middleware/auth.js`.

### Hard rules — do not weaken

- The mobile app **never** calls Legacy directly. There is exactly one
  base URL (`env.apiBaseUrl`); no Legacy host strings anywhere in `src/`.
- `INTERNAL_API_SECRET` lives only in Hono's process env. Never read,
  log, ship, or forward it from anywhere the client can reach.
- Identity used for data scoping (`X-Tenant-ID`, `X-User-ID`,
  `X-Agreement-Number`) is derived from the verified Firebase JWT in
  `resolveTenant`. Legacy MUST ignore identity values arriving in body
  or query — never reintroduce that pattern in a new route.
- `resolveTenant` validates the `X-Tenant-Id` header against
  `user_tenants` (superadmins excepted). Do not bypass that check.
- On logout, clear: TanStack Query cache + all `roomalyzer_*` storage
  keys + Firebase session. Already wired in `AuthProvider` — preserve.

### Known gaps — keep in mind when editing auth / middleware

Accepted today, but tighten when you touch the area:

1. **JWT is not tenant-bound.** A leaked Firebase token can be replayed
   against any tenant the user is a member of by varying `X-Tenant-Id`.
   If a "tenant session" token is ever introduced, prefer it over the
   raw Firebase token for tenant-scoped calls.
2. **Dev bypass via `X-Dev-User-Email`.** `auth.js` falls back to the
   bypass when `NODE_ENV !== 'production'` — including when Firebase
   verification fails. Any non-prod environment (preview, staging) MUST
   set `NODE_ENV=production`. Verify the header is also stripped from
   the prod CORS `allowHeaders`.
3. **API-key auth has no user.** `apiKeyAuth` sets `tenantId` but not
   `user`. A route that calls `legacyRequest` from an API-key context
   sends `X-User-ID: ""` to Legacy, which breaks audit logging. Decide
   explicitly: deny, or attribute to a system service-account user.
4. **Legacy error pass-through.** `legacyRequest` propagates the raw
   Legacy response on failure. Normalise / redact in the route handler
   before returning to the client — no PHP stack traces or DB errors
   to the mobile app.
5. **No app attestation.** The mobile bundle is not bound via Apple
   App Attest or Play Integrity. A user with a valid Firebase login can
   call any endpoint from any client. This is accepted B2B risk — do
   NOT design endpoints that assume "only our app can reach this".

### On-device storage — what goes where

- Firebase ID + refresh tokens → `expo-secure-store` (Keychain on iOS,
  EncryptedSharedPreferences on Android). Wired in
  `src/services/auth/firebase.ts`.
- MMKV (`src/lib/storage.ts`) is fine for non-secret prefs: active
  tenant id, active module, last-used period, UI toggles.
- Never put bearer tokens, API keys, or `INTERNAL_*` values into MMKV
  or AsyncStorage. Neither is encrypted by default on Android.

---

## Testing Against External APIs — Safety Rules

When hitting the Hono or Legacy API during development:
- NEVER delete, update, or modify existing data as part of automated
  tests.
- Only delete data you created in the same session, and use clearly
  throwaway names (`"TEST — delete me"`).
- Prefer GET over POST/PUT/DELETE unless the specific behavior is what
  you're testing.
- These rules apply to the agent, not the user acting through the UI.

---

## Legacy API Failures — Report, Don't Workaround

This rule is copied verbatim from the web repo and applies identically.

If a Legacy API endpoint does not respond as expected:
1. Stop immediately.
2. Tell the user: which endpoint, what it returned, what was expected.
3. Ask how to proceed.

NEVER:
- Store Legacy data in our own local storage as a "bridge".
- Create mock overrides that silently replace broken endpoints.
- Mention the problem as a footnote and build a workaround.

The fix belongs on the Legacy side.

---

## Production-Quality Code

- Functional components only.
- Handle loading / error / empty states on every screen. Never leave
  the user staring at a blank screen.
- Every async call wrapped in try/catch (or `useQuery` error surface).
- Never trust client input; validate before sending to the API.
- No secrets in the client bundle. Values go in `app.json.extra` or
  `EXPO_PUBLIC_*` env vars (publicly inspectable, so only public keys).

---

## File Naming

- Routes: lowercase with brackets (`app/sensor/[id].tsx`)
- Components: PascalCase (`PageHeading.tsx`, `SensorPicker.tsx`)
- Hooks: `use*` camelCase (`useLocationFilter.ts`, `useSensors.ts`)
- Services / lib: camelCase (`apiClient.ts`, `storage.ts`)
- Locales: lowercase json (`da.json`)

### Imports
```tsx
// 1. React & libraries
import { useState } from 'react';
import { View, Text } from 'react-native';

// 2. Absolute @/ imports (src/)
import { colors } from '@/theme';
import { useSensors } from '@/features/indeklima/hooks';

// 3. Relative imports (same feature)
import SensorRow from './SensorRow';
```

---

## Consistency Checklist (every new screen)

- [ ] All text through `t()` with keys in all 4 locale files
- [ ] Uses `<PageHeading>` — no hand-rolled title
- [ ] Uses theme primitives (colors, typography, spacing)
- [ ] Uses `<Icon>` — no direct `@expo/vector-icons` import
- [ ] Loading / error / empty states handled
- [ ] Pull-to-refresh on any list
- [ ] Touch targets >= 44px
- [ ] Works in both iOS + Android simulators (visual parity)
- [ ] Location-based data filtered through `useLocationFilter`
- [ ] API access via generated typed client — no ad-hoc fetch
- [ ] Tenant-aware (scoped queries via `X-Tenant-Id`)
